<p>A <b>magnetic field</b> (sometimes called <b>B-field</b><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magneti=
c_field#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Physical_field" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Physical field">physical=
 field</a> that describes the magnetic influence on moving <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_charge" title=3D"Electric charge">electri=
c charges</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_currents" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electric currents">electric currents</a>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-feynman_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-feynman-2"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D=
"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Location: ch1">:=E2=80=8Ach1=E2=80=8A</sp=
an></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and magnetic mater=
ials. A moving charge in a magnetic field experiences a force perpendicular=
 to its own <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Vel=
ocity">velocity</a> and to the magnetic field.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-feynman_2=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_f=
ield#cite_note-feynman-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span t=
itle=3D"Location: ch13">:=E2=80=8Ach13=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Purcell3ed_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Purcell3ed-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refer=
ence nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 278">:=E2=80=8A278=E2=80=8A</span></sup> =
A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permanent_magnet" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Permanent magnet">permanent magnet</a>'s magnetic field pu=
lls on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferromagnetic_material" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ferromagnetic material">ferromagnetic materials=
</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron" title=3D"Iron">=
iron</a>, and attracts or repels other magnets. In addition, a nonuniform m=
agnetic field exerts minuscule forces on "nonmagnetic" materials by three o=
ther magnetic effects: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paramagneti=
sm" title=3D"Paramagnetism">paramagnetism</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Diamagnetism" title=3D"Diamagnetism">diamagnetism</a>, and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiferromagnetism" title=3D"Antiferr=
omagnetism">antiferromagnetism</a>, although these forces are usually so sm=
all they can only be detected by laboratory equipment. Magnetic fields surr=
ound magnetized materials, electric currents, and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Electric_field" title=3D"Electric field">electric fields</a=
> varying in time. Since both strength and direction of a magnetic field ma=
y vary with location, it is described mathematically by a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathemat=
ics)">function</a> assigning a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean vector">vector</a> to each point of space=
, called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_field" title=3D"=
Vector field">vector field</a> (more precisely, a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pseudovector" title=3D"Pseudovector">pseudovector</a> field=
).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Electromagnetics">Electroma=
gnetics</h2></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetics" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Electromagnetics">electromagnetics</a>, the term <i>ma=
gnetic field</i> is used for two distinct but closely related vector fields=
 denoted by the symbols <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> and <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Unit=
s">International System of Units</a>, the unit of <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>B</b></span>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_flux" tit=
le=3D"Magnetic flux">magnetic flux</a> density, is the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesla_(unit)" title=3D"Tesla (unit)">tesla</a> (in SI =
base units: kilogram per second squared per ampere),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_=
5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_=
field#cite_note-:1-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=
=3D"Page: 21">:=E2=80=8A21=E2=80=8A</span></sup> which is equivalent to <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (unit)=
">newton</a> per meter per ampere. The unit of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H=
</b></span>, magnetic field strength, is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ampere" title=3D"Ampere">ampere</a> per meter (A/m).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-:1_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
gnetic_field#cite_note-:1-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Page: 22">:=E2=80=8A22=E2=80=8A</span></sup> <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><b>B</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> differ in =
how they take the medium and/or magnetization into account. In <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacuum" title=3D"Vacuum">vacuum</a>, the two f=
ields are related through the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacu=
um_permeability" title=3D"Vacuum permeability">vacuum permeability</a>, <sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbf {=
B} /\mu _{0}=3D\mathbf {H} }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">H</mi>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {B} /=
\mu _{0}=3D\mathbf {H} }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/773a5eb3020e0a6c574f625c487a7e3d8eaec1bf" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:10.709ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \m=
athbf {B} /\mu _{0}=3D\mathbf {H} }"></span>; in a magnetized material, the=
 quantities on each side of this equation differ by the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetization" title=3D"Magnetization">magnetization<=
/a> field of the material.
</p><p>Magnetic fields are produced by moving electric charges and the intr=
insic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_moment" title=3D"Ma=
gnetic moment">magnetic moments</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Elementary_particle" title=3D"Elementary particle">elementary particle=
s</a> associated with a fundamental quantum property, their <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_(physics)" title=3D"Spin (physics)">spin</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jiles_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Jiles-6"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-feynman_2-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-feynman-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference=
 nowrap"><span title=3D"Location: ch1">:=E2=80=8Ach1=E2=80=8A</span></sup> =
Magnetic fields and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_field=
" title=3D"Electric field">electric fields</a> are interrelated and are bot=
h components of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagneti=
c_force" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electromagnetic force">electromagne=
tic force</a>, one of the four <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fun=
damental_force" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fundamental force">fundament=
al forces</a> of nature.
</p><p>Magnetic fields are used throughout modern technology, particularly =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_engineering" title=
=3D"Electrical engineering">electrical engineering</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromechanics" title=3D"Electromechanics">elect=
romechanics</a>. Rotating magnetic fields are used in both <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_motor" title=3D"Electric motor">electric =
motors</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_generator"=
 title=3D"Electric generator">generators</a>. The interaction of magnetic f=
ields in electric devices such as transformers is conceptualized and invest=
igated as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_circuit" title=
=3D"Magnetic circuit">magnetic circuits</a>. Magnetic forces give informati=
on about the charge carriers in a material through the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hall_effect" title=3D"Hall effect">Hall effect</a>. Th=
e Earth produces <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_magneti=
c_field" title=3D"Earth's magnetic field">its own magnetic field</a>, which=
 shields the Earth's ozone layer from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Solar_wind" title=3D"Solar wind">solar wind</a> and is important in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navigation" title=3D"Navigation">=
navigation</a> using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass" ti=
tle=3D"Compass">compass</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Description">Description</h=
2></div>
<p>The force on an electric charge depends on its location, speed, and dire=
ction; two vector fields are used to describe this force.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-feynman_2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Magnetic_field#cite_note-feynman-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowr=
ap"><span title=3D"Location: ch1">:=E2=80=8Ach1=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The f=
irst is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_field" title=
=3D"Electric field">electric field</a>, which describes the force acting on=
 a stationary charge and gives the component of the force that is independe=
nt of motion. The magnetic field, in contrast, describes the component of t=
he force that is proportional to both the speed and direction of charged pa=
rticles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-feynman_2-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-feynman-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Location: ch13">:=E2=80=8Ach1=
3=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The field is defined by the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_force_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lorentz=
 force law">Lorentz force law</a> and is, at each instant, perpendicular to=
 both the motion of the charge and the force it experiences.
</p><p>There are two different, but closely related vector fields which are=
 both sometimes called the "magnetic field" written <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><b>B</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magne=
tic_field#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 1<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While both the best names for these =
fields and exact interpretation of what these fields represent has been the=
 subject of long running debate, there is wide agreement about how the unde=
rlying physics work.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Histori=
cally, the term "magnetic field" was reserved for <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>H</b></span> while using other terms for <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b>=
</span>, but many recent textbooks use the term "magnetic field" to describ=
e <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> as well as or in place of <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ex03_9-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-e=
x03-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 2<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
There are many alternative names for both (see sidebars).
</p>
