<p>The magnetic field vector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> at any=
 point can be defined as the vector that, when used in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_force_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Lorentz force law">Lorentz force law</a>, correctly predicts the force on a=
 charged particle at that point:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-purcell2ed_12-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite=
_note-purcell2ed-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Griffiths3ed_13-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cit=
e_note-Griffiths3ed-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span t=
itle=3D"Page: 204">:=E2=80=8A204=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"equation-box" style=3D"margin: 0 0 0 1.6em;padding: 5px; bord=
er-width:2px; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0,115,207); color: inh=
erit;text-align: center; display: table"><b>Lorentz force law</b>  (<i><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"Euclidean v=
ector">vector</a> form, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internatio=
nal_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">SI units</a></=
i>)
<p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"=
mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math=
 xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbf {F} =3Dq\mathbf {E} +q(\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} )}">
