l-align: -1.005ex; width:21.175ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
mathbf {F} _{\text{magnetic}}=3Dq(\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} ).}"></spa=
n>
</p><p>Using the definition of the cross product, the magnetic force can al=
so be written as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(physics=
)" title=3D"Scalar (physics)">scalar</a> equation:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-purce=
ll2ed_12-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
gnetic_field#cite_note-purcell2ed-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference no=
wrap"><span title=3D"Page: 357">:=E2=80=8A357=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle F_{\text{magnetic}}=3DqvB\sin(\theta )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>F</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>magnetic</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mi>v</mi>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mi>sin</mi>
        <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=B8<!-- =CE=B8 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle F_{\text{magn=
etic}}=3DqvB\sin(\theta )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/2b7c35be48f0f9efbcff642408d09df2c9e0ad58" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -1.005ex; width:21.413ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle F=
_{\text{magnetic}}=3DqvB\sin(\theta )}"></span>
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>magnetic</sub></span>, <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v</span>, and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span> are the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norm_(mathematics)" title=3D"Norm (mathematic=
s)">scalar magnitude</a> of their respective vectors, and <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> is the angle between=
 the velocity of the particle and the magnetic field. The vector <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is <i>defined</i> as the vector field necessa=
ry to make the Lorentz force law correctly describe the motion of a charged=
 particle. In other words,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-purcell2ed_12-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-p=
urcell2ed-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pag=
es: 173=E2=80=934">:=E2=80=8A<a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" hr=
ef=3D"https://archive.org/details/electricitymagne00purc_621/page/n192">173=
</a>=E2=80=934=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>[T]he command, "Measure the directio=
n and magnitude of the vector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> at su=
ch and such a place," calls for the following operations: Take a particle o=
f known charge <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i></span>. Measure the force o=
n <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i></span> at rest, to determine <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span>. Then measure the force on the particle when i=
ts velocity is <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span>; repeat with <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> in some other direction. Now find a <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> that makes the Lorentz force law fit all =
these results=E2=80=94that is the magnetic field at the place in question.<=
/p></blockquote>
