<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Measurement">Measurement</h=
3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetometer" title=
=3D"Magnetometer">Magnetometer</a></div>
<p>An instrument used to measure the local magnetic field is known as a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetometer" title=3D"Magnetometer">=
magnetometer</a>. Important classes of magnetometers include using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_coil" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Search coil">induction magnetometers</a> (or search-coil magnetometers)=
 which measure only varying magnetic fields, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Magnetometer#Rotating_coil_magnetometer" title=3D"Magnetometer">=
rotating coil magnetometers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
all_effect" title=3D"Hall effect">Hall effect</a> magnetometers, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proton_magnetometer" title=3D"Proton magneto=
meter">NMR magnetometers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SQUI=
D" title=3D"SQUID">SQUID magnetometers</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Magnetometer#Fluxgate_magnetometer" title=3D"Magnetometer">fl=
uxgate magnetometers</a>. The magnetic fields of distant <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_object" title=3D"Astronomical object">a=
stronomical objects</a> are measured through their effects on local charged=
 particles. For instance, electrons spiraling around a field line produce <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synchrotron_radiation" title=3D"Syn=
chrotron radiation">synchrotron radiation</a> that is detectable in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio_waves" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Radio waves">radio waves</a>. The finest precision for a magnetic field=
 measurement was attained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravi=
ty_Probe_B" title=3D"Gravity Probe B">Gravity Probe B</a> at <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6982500000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5&nb=
sp;aT</span> (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6982500000000=
000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.1=
5em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9218</sup>&nbsp;T</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnet=
ic_field#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Visualization">Visualizatio=
n<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Magnetic_field_line"></span></h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_line" title=3D=
"Field line">Field line</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:342px;max-width:342px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"theader">Visualizing magnetic fields</d=
iv></div><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:239px;ma=
x-width:239px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:161px;overflow:hid=
den"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File=
:Magnet0873.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https:/=
/upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Magnet0873.png/250px-Mag=
net0873.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"237" height=3D"161" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"1106" data-file-height=3D"751"></a></span></=
div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:99px;max-width:99px"><div c=
lass=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:161px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"=
mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Magnetic_field_near_=
pole.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload=
.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Magnetic_field_near_pole.svg/12=
0px-Magnetic_field_near_pole.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"97" heigh=
t=3D"162" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"300" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"500"></a></span></div></div></div><div class=3D"trow" style=3D"display=
:flex"><div class=3D"thumbcaption">Left: the direction of magnetic <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_line" title=3D"Field line">field li=
nes</a> represented by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_filing=
s" title=3D"Iron filings">iron filings</a> sprinkled on paper placed above =
a bar magnet.<br>
Right: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass" title=3D"Compass">=
compass</a> needles point in the direction of the local magnetic field, tow=
ards a magnet's south pole and away from its north pole.</div></div></div><=
/div>
<p>The field can be visualized by a set of <i>magnetic field lines</i>, tha=
t follow the direction of the field at each point. The lines can be constru=
cted by measuring the strength and direction of the magnetic field at a lar=
ge number of points (or at every point in space). Then, mark each location =
with an arrow (called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(ge=
ometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vector (geometry)">vector</a>) poin=
ting in the direction of the local magnetic field with its magnitude propor=
tional to the strength of the magnetic field. Connecting these arrows then =
forms a set of magnetic field lines. The direction of the magnetic field at=
 any point is parallel to the direction of nearby field lines, and the loca=
l density of field lines can be made proportional to its strength. Magnetic=
 field lines are like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streamlines,=
_streaklines,_and_pathlines" title=3D"Streamlines, streaklines, and pathlin=
es">streamlines</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynam=
ics" title=3D"Fluid dynamics">fluid flow</a>, in that they represent a cont=
inuous distribution, and a different resolution would show more or fewer li=
nes.
</p><p>An advantage of using magnetic field lines as a representation is th=
at many laws of magnetism (and electromagnetism) can be stated completely a=
nd concisely using simple concepts such as the "number" of field lines thro=
ugh a surface. These concepts can be quickly "translated" to their mathemat=
ical form. For example, the number of field lines through a given surface i=
s the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_integral" title=3D"S=
urface integral">surface integral</a> of the magnetic field.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-purcell2ed_12-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-purcell2ed-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 237">:=E2=80=8A237=E2=80=8A</span></su=
p>
</p><p>Various phenomena "display" magnetic field lines as though the field=
 lines were physical phenomena. For example, iron filings placed in a magne=
tic field form lines that correspond to "field lines".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-e=
x07_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magn=
etic_field#cite_note-ex07-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 5<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Magnetic field "lines" are al=
so visually displayed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurora_(a=
stronomy)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aurora (astronomy)">polar auroras=
</a>, in which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plasma_(physics)" t=
itle=3D"Plasma (physics)">plasma</a> particle dipole interactions create vi=
sible streaks of light that line up with the local direction of Earth's mag=
netic field.
</p><p>Field lines can be used as a qualitative tool to visualize magnetic =
forces. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferromagnetic" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ferromagnetic">ferromagnetic</a> substances like <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron" title=3D"Iron">iron</a> and in =
plasmas, magnetic forces can be understood by imagining that the field line=
s exert a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell_stress_tensor" t=
itle=3D"Maxwell stress tensor">tension</a>, (like a rubber band) along thei=
r length, and a pressure perpendicular to their length on neighboring field=
 lines. "Unlike" poles of magnets attract because they are linked by many f=
ield lines; "like" poles repel because their field lines do not meet, but r=
un parallel, pushing on each other.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Magnetic_field_of_permanent=
_magnets">Magnetic field of permanent magnets</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_moment#Mode=
ls" title=3D"Magnetic moment">Magnetic moment =C2=A7&nbsp;Models</a></div>
<p><i>Permanent magnets</i> are objects that produce their own persistent m=
agnetic fields. They are made of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
erromagnetism" title=3D"Ferromagnetism">ferromagnetic</a> materials, such a=
s iron and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nickel" title=3D"Nickel=
">nickel</a>, that have been magnetized, and they have both a north and a s=
outh pole.
</p><p>The magnetic field of permanent magnets can be quite complicated, es=
pecially near the magnet. The magnetic field of a small<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
ex05_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mag=
netic_field#cite_note-ex05-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 6<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> straight magnet is proportio=
nal to the magnet's <i>strength</i> (called its <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Magnetic_dipole_moment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Magnet=
ic dipole moment">magnetic dipole moment</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</=
b></span>). The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dipole#Field_of_a_=
static_magnetic_dipole" title=3D"Dipole">equations</a> are non-trivial and =
depend on the distance from the magnet and the orientation of the magnet. F=
or simple magnets, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span> points in the di=
rection of a line drawn from the south to the north pole of the magnet. Fli=
pping a bar magnet is equivalent to rotating its <span class=3D"texhtml"><b=
>m</b></span> by 180 degrees.
</p><p>The magnetic field of larger magnets can be obtained by modeling the=
m as a collection of a large number of small magnets called <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dipole" title=3D"Dipole">dipoles</a> each having =
their own <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span>. The magnetic field produ=
ced by the magnet then is the net magnetic field of these dipoles; any net =
force on the magnet is a result of adding up the forces on the individual d=
ipoles.
</p><p>There are two simplified models for the nature of these dipoles: the=
 <a class=3D"mw-selflink-fragment" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
gnetic_field#Magnetic_pole_model">magnetic pole model</a> and the <a class=
=3D"mw-selflink-fragment" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fi=
eld#Amperian_loop_model">Amperian loop model</a>. These two models produce =
two different magnetic fields, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>. Outside a material, though, the tw=
o are identical (to a multiplicative constant) so that in many cases the di=
stinction can be ignored. This is particularly true for magnetic fields, su=
ch as those due to electric currents, that are not generated by magnetic ma=
terials.
</p><p>A realistic model of magnetism is more complicated than either of th=
ese models; neither model fully explains why materials are magnetic. The mo=
nopole model has no experimental support. The Amperian loop model explains =
some, but not all of a material's magnetic moment. The model predicts that =
the motion of electrons within an atom are connected to those electrons' <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron_magnetic_moment#Orbital_mag=
netic_dipole_moment" title=3D"Electron magnetic moment">orbital magnetic di=
pole moment</a>, and these orbital moments do contribute to the magnetism s=
een at the macroscopic level. However, the motion of electrons is not class=
ical, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_magnetic_moment=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spin magnetic moment">spin magnetic moment=
</a> of electrons (which is not explained by either model) is also a signif=
icant contribution to the total moment of magnets.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetic_pole_model">Magnet=
ic pole model</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_monopole" title=
=3D"Magnetic monopole">Magnetic monopole</a></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:VFPt_dipole_electric.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"htt=
ps://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/VFPt_dipole_electric=
.svg/250px-VFPt_dipole_electric.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" h=
eight=3D"200" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600" data-file-h=
eight=3D"600"></a><figcaption>The magnetic pole model: two opposing poles, =
North (+) and South (=E2=88=92), separated by a distance d produce a <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field (lines).</figcaption></figure>
<p>Historically, early physics textbooks would model the force and torques =
between two magnets as due to magnetic poles repelling or attracting each o=
ther in the same manner as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cou=
lomb_force" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coulomb force">Coulomb force</a>=
 between electric charges. At the microscopic level, this model contradicts=
 the experimental evidence, and the pole model of magnetism is no longer th=
e typical way to introduce the concept.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Griffiths3ed_13-=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fi=
eld#cite_note-Griffiths3ed-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><=
span title=3D"Page: 258">:=E2=80=8A258=E2=80=8A</span></sup> However, it is=
 still sometimes used as a macroscopic model for ferromagnetism due to its =
mathematical simplicity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-23"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In this model, a magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-fi=
eld is produced by fictitious <i>magnetic charges</i> that are spread over =
the surface of each pole. These <i>magnetic charges</i> are in fact related=
 to the magnetization field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span>. The <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field, therefore, is analogous to the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_field" title=3D"Electric=
 field">electric field</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span>, which s=
tarts at a positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_charg=
e" title=3D"Electric charge">electric charge</a> and ends at a negative ele=
ctric charge. Near the north pole, therefore, all <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>H</b></span>-field lines point away from the north pole (whether inside t=
he magnet or out) while near the south pole all <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=
H</b></span>-field lines point toward the south pole (whether inside the ma=
gnet or out). Too, a north pole feels a force in the direction of the <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field while the force on the south pole =
is opposite to the <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field.
</p><p>In the magnetic pole model, the elementary magnetic dipole <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span> is formed by two opposite magnetic poles of =
pole strength <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i><sub>m</sub></span> separated=
 by a small distance vector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>d</b></span>, such t=
hat <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b> =3D <i>q</i><sub>m</sub>=E2=80=89<b>d<=
/b></span>. The magnetic pole model predicts correctly the field <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> both inside and outside magnetic materials, i=
n particular the fact that <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> is oppos=
ite to the magnetization field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> insi=
de a permanent magnet.
</p><p>Since it is based on the fictitious idea of a <i>magnetic charge den=
sity</i>, the pole model has limitations. Magnetic poles cannot exist apart=
 from each other as electric charges can, but always come in north=E2=80=93=
south pairs. If a magnetized object is divided in half, a new pole appears =
on the surface of each piece, so each has a pair of complementary poles. Th=
e magnetic pole model does not account for magnetism that is produced by el=
ectric currents, nor the inherent connection between <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_momentum" title=3D"Angular momentum">angular mom=
entum</a> and magnetism.
</p><p>The pole model usually treats magnetic charge as a mathematical abst=
raction, rather than a physical property of particles. However, a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_monopole" title=3D"Magnetic mono=
pole">magnetic monopole</a> is a hypothetical particle (or class of particl=
es) that physically has only one magnetic pole (either a north pole or a so=
uth pole). In other words, it would possess a "magnetic charge" analogous t=
o an electric charge. Magnetic field lines would start or end on magnetic m=
onopoles, so if they exist, they would give exceptions to the rule that mag=
netic field lines neither start nor end. Some theories (such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Unified_Theory" title=3D"Grand Unified =
Theory">Grand Unified Theories</a>) have predicted the existence of magneti=
c monopoles, but so far, none have been observed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Amperian_loop_model">Amperi=
an loop model</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_dipole" tit=
le=3D"Magnetic dipole">Magnetic dipole</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_magnetic_moment" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spin magnetic moment">Spin magnetic moment</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micromagnetism" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Micromagnetism">Micromagnetism</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:312px;max-width:312px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"theader">The Amperian loop model</div><=
/div><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:154px;max-wi=
dth:154px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:152px;overflow:hidden"=
><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VFP=
t_dipole_magnetic3.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/56/VFPt_dipole_magne=
tic3.svg/250px-VFPt_dipole_magnetic3.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1=
52" height=3D"152" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600" data-f=
ile-height=3D"600"></a></span></div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"w=
idth:154px;max-width:154px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:152px=
;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/File:VFPt_dipole_animation_magnetic.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/3/3b/VFPt_dipole_animation_magnetic.gif/220px-VFPt_dipole_animation_mag=
netic.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"152" height=3D"152" class=3D"mw-file=
-element" data-file-width=3D"220" data-file-height=3D"220"></a></span></div=
></div></div><div class=3D"trow" style=3D"display:flex"><div class=3D"thumb=
caption">A current loop (ring) that goes into the page at the x and comes o=
ut at the dot produces a <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-field (lin=
es). As the radius of the current loop shrinks, the fields produced become =
identical to an abstract "magnetostatic dipole" (represented by an arrow po=
inting to the right).</div></div></div></div>
<p>In the model developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%=
C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re" title=3D"Andr=C3=A9-Marie Amp=C3=A8re">Ampere</a>,=
 the elementary magnetic dipole that makes up all magnets is a sufficiently=
 small Amperian loop with current <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>I</i></span> a=
nd loop area <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i></span>. The dipole moment of =
this loop is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =3D <i>IA</i></span>.
</p><p>These magnetic dipoles produce a magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b=
>B</b></span>-field.
</p><p>The magnetic field of a magnetic dipole is depicted in the figure. F=
rom outside, the ideal magnetic dipole is identical to that of an ideal ele=
ctric dipole of the same strength. Unlike the electric dipole, a magnetic d=
ipole is properly modeled as a current loop having a current <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>I</i></span> and an area <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></spa=
n>. Such a current loop has a magnetic moment of
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle m=3DIa,}">
