            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">m</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {F} =
=3D{\boldsymbol {\nabla }}\left(\mathbf {m} \cdot \mathbf {B} \right),}</an=
notation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/2000ebec9a4d95147f858853f908ec09e1c0c23b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:16.044ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
mathbf {F} =3D{\boldsymbol {\nabla }}\left(\mathbf {m} \cdot \mathbf {B} \r=
ight),}"></span>
</p><p>where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient" title=
=3D"Gradient">gradient</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=E2=88=87</b></span> =
is the change of the quantity <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b> =C2=B7 <b>B<=
/b></span> per unit distance and the direction is that of maximum increase =
of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b> =C2=B7 <b>B</b></span>. The <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product" title=3D"Dot product">dot produc=
t</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b> =C2=B7 <b>B</b> =3D <i>mB</i>cos(<i>=
=CE=B8</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> and <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i></span> represent the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Magnitude_(vector)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Magnitude=
 (vector)">magnitude</a> of the <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> vectors and <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>=CE=B8</i></span> is the angle between them. If <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><b>m</b></span> is in the same direction as <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B<=
/b></span> then the dot product is positive and the gradient points "uphill=
" pulling the magnet into regions of higher <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b=
></span>-field (more strictly larger <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b> =C2=
=B7 <b>B</b></span>). This equation is strictly only valid for magnets of z=
ero size, but is often a good approximation for not too large magnets. The =
magnetic force on larger magnets is determined by dividing them into smalle=
r regions each having their own <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span> the=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"Integral">sum=
ming up the forces on each of these very small regions</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetic_torque_on_permanen=
t_magnets">Magnetic torque on permanent magnets</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_torque" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Magnetic torque">Magnetic torque</a></div>
<p>If two like poles of two separate magnets are brought near each other, a=
nd one of the magnets is allowed to turn, it promptly rotates to align itse=
lf with the first. In this example, the magnetic field of the stationary ma=
gnet creates a <i>magnetic torque</i> on the magnet that is free to rotate.=
 This magnetic torque <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=CF=84</b></span> tends to=
 align a magnet's poles with the magnetic field lines. A compass, therefore=
, turns to align itself with Earth's magnetic field.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:312px;max-width:312px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"theader">Torque on a dipole</div></div>=
<div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:166px;max-width:1=
