<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interactions_with_electric_=
currents">Interactions with electric currents</h2></div>
<p>Currents of electric charges both generate a magnetic field and feel a f=
orce due to magnetic B-fields.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetic_field_due_to_movin=
g_charges_and_electric_currents">Magnetic field due to moving charges and e=
lectric currents</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnet" titl=
e=3D"Electromagnet">Electromagnet</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Biot%E2%80%93Savart_law" title=3D"Biot=E2=80=93Savart law">Biot=E2=80=
=93Savart law</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amp%C3%A8re=
%27s_circuital_law" title=3D"Amp=C3=A8re's circuital law">Amp=C3=A8re's law=
</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Manoderecha.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/3/3e/Manoderecha.svg/250px-Manoderecha.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" =
width=3D"250" height=3D"185" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4=
07" data-file-height=3D"301"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Right_hand_grip_rule" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Right hand =
grip rule">Right hand grip rule</a>: a current flowing in the direction of =
the white arrow produces a magnetic field shown by the red arrows.</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>All moving charged particles produce magnetic fields. Moving <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_particle" title=3D"Point particle">poin=
t</a> charges, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron" t=
itle=3D"Electron">electrons</a>, produce complicated but well known magneti=
c fields that depend on the charge, velocity, and acceleration of the parti=
cles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Magnetic field lines form in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Concentric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Concentric">concentric</a> cir=
cles around a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (geometry)">cylindrical</a> curren=
t-carrying conductor, such as a length of wire. The direction of such a mag=
netic field can be determined by using the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Right-hand_grip_rule" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Right-hand g=
rip rule">right-hand grip rule</a>" (see figure at right). The strength of =
the magnetic field decreases with distance from the wire. (For an infinite =
length wire the strength is inversely proportional to the distance.)
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VFPt_cylindrical_tightly-wound_coil-and-bar-ma=
gnet-comparison_stacked.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"http=
s://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/VFPt_cylindrical_tigh=
tly-wound_coil-and-bar-magnet-comparison_stacked.svg/250px-VFPt_cylindrical=
_tightly-wound_coil-and-bar-magnet-comparison_stacked.svg.png" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"150" height=3D"233" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"795"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solenoid" title=3D"Solenoid">Solenoid</a> with electric=
 current running through it behaves like a magnet.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Bending a current-carrying wire into a loop concentrates the magnetic fi=
eld inside the loop while weakening it outside. Bending a wire into multipl=
e closely spaced loops to form a coil or "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Solenoid" title=3D"Solenoid">solenoid</a>" enhances this effect. A =
device so formed around an iron <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
gnetic_core" title=3D"Magnetic core">core</a> may act as an <i>electromagne=
t</i>, generating a strong, well-controlled magnetic field. An infinitely l=
ong cylindrical electromagnet has a uniform magnetic field inside, and no m=
agnetic field outside. A finite length electromagnet produces a magnetic fi=
eld that looks similar to that produced by a uniform permanent magnet, with=
 its strength and polarity determined by the current flowing through the co=
il.
</p><p>The magnetic field generated by a steady current <span class=3D"texh=
tml">I</span> (a constant flow of electric charges, in which charge neither=
 accumulates nor is depleted at any point)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ex12_29-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#c=
ite_note-ex12-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 8<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is described by the <i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biot%E2%80%93Savart_law" title=3D"Biot=E2=80=93Savar=
t law">Biot=E2=80=93Savart law</a></i>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Griffiths4ed_28-=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fi=
eld#cite_note-Griffiths4ed-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><=
span title=3D"Page: 224">:=E2=80=8A224=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
