</p><p>In a modified form that accounts for time varying electric fields, A=
mp=C3=A8re's law is one of four <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
xwell%27s_equations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's equations</a> =
that describe electricity and magnetism.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Force_on_moving_charges_and=
_current">Force on moving charges and current</h3></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Force_on_a_charged_particle=
">Force on a charged particle</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_force" title=
=3D"Lorentz force">Lorentz force</a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charged_particle" title=3D"Ch=
arged particle">charged particle</a> moving in a <span class=3D"texhtml"><b=
>B</b></span>-field experiences a <i>sideways</i> force that is proportiona=
l to the strength of the magnetic field, the component of the velocity that=
 is perpendicular to the magnetic field and the charge of the particle. Thi=
s force is known as the <i>Lorentz force</i>, and is given by
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \mathbf {F} =3Dq\mathbf {E} +q\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} ,}=
">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">F</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">E</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">v</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {F} =
=3Dq\mathbf {E} +q\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/daba70054e9cc1b66449c534969a45695657700f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.671ex; width:18.317ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
mathbf {F} =3Dq\mathbf {E} +q\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B} ,}"></span>
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>F</b></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a>, <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>q</i></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_=
charge" title=3D"Electric charge">electric charge</a> of the particle, <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> is the instantaneous <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Velocity">velocity</a> of the par=
ticle, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is the magnetic field (i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesla_(unit)" title=3D"Tesla (un=
it)">teslas</a>).
</p><p>The Lorentz force is always perpendicular to both the velocity of th=
e particle and the magnetic field that created it. When a charged particle =
moves in a static magnetic field, it traces a helical path in which the hel=
ix axis is parallel to the magnetic field, and in which the speed of the pa=
rticle remains constant. Because the magnetic force is always perpendicular=
 to the motion, the magnetic field can do no <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mechanical_work" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mechanical work"=
>work</a> on an isolated charge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-32"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It can only do wo=
rk indirectly, via the electric field generated by a changing magnetic fiel=
d. It is often claimed that the magnetic force can do work to a non-element=
ary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_dipole" title=3D"Magn=
etic dipole">magnetic dipole</a>, or to charged particles whose motion is c=
onstrained by other forces, but this is incorrect<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Deissl=
er_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magne=
tic_field#cite_note-Deissler-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> because the work in those case=
s is performed by the electric forces of the charges deflected by the magne=
tic field.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Force_on_current-carrying_w=
ire">Force on current-carrying wire</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_force" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Laplace force">Laplace force</a></div>
<p>The force on a current carrying wire is similar to that of a moving char=
ge as expected since a current carrying wire is a collection of moving char=
ges. A current-carrying wire feels a force in the presence of a magnetic fi=
eld. The Lorentz force on a macroscopic current is often referred to as the=
 <i>Laplace force</i>.
Consider a conductor of length <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=E2=84=93</i></sp=
an>, cross section <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i></span>, and charge <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i></span> due to electric current <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>i</i></span>. If this conductor is placed in a magnetic field o=
f magnitude <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i></span> that makes an angle <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">=CE=B8</span> with the velocity of charges in the cond=
uctor, the force exerted on a single charge <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i=
></span> is
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle F=3DqvB\sin \theta ,}">
