<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relation_between_H_and_B">R=
elation between H and B</h2></div>
<p>The formulas derived for the magnetic field above are correct when deali=
ng with the entire current. A magnetic material placed inside a magnetic fi=
eld, though, generates its own <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bou=
nd_current" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bound current">bound current</a>=
, which can be a challenge to calculate. (This bound current is due to the =
sum of atomic sized current loops and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Spin_(physics)" title=3D"Spin (physics)">spin</a> of the subatomic =
particles such as electrons that make up the material.) The <span class=3D"=
texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field as defined above helps factor out this bound=
 current; but to see how, it helps to introduce the concept of <i>magnetiza=
tion</i> first.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetization">Magnetizatio=
n</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetization" title=
=3D"Magnetization">Magnetization</a></div>
<p>The <i>magnetization</i> vector field <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></=
span> represents how strongly a region of material is magnetized. It is def=
ined as the net <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_dipole_mo=
ment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Magnetic dipole moment">magnetic dipol=
e moment</a> per unit volume of that region. The magnetization of a uniform=
 magnet is therefore a material constant, equal to the magnetic moment <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>m</b></span> of the magnet divided by its volume. Si=
nce the SI unit of magnetic moment is A=E2=8B=85m<sup>2</sup>, the SI unit =
of magnetization <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> is ampere per mete=
r, identical to that of the <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field.
</p><p>The magnetization <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> field of a=
 region points in the direction of the average magnetic dipole moment in th=
at region. Magnetization field lines, therefore, begin near the magnetic so=
uth pole and ends near the magnetic north pole. (Magnetization does not exi=
st outside the magnet.)
</p><p>In the Amperian loop model, the magnetization is due to combining ma=
ny tiny Amperian loops to form a resultant current called <i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bound_current" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bo=
und current">bound current</a></i>. This bound current, then, is the source=
 of the magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> field due to the m=
agnet. Given the definition of the magnetic dipole, the magnetization field=
 follows a similar law to that of Ampere's law:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cit=
e_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \oint \mathbf {M} \cdot \mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}=3DI_{=
\mathrm {b} },}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=E2=88=AE<!-- =E2=88=AE --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">M</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold-italic">=E2=84=93<!-- =E2=84=93 --></mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>I</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">b</mi>
