</p><p>The magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field, therefor=
e, re-factors the bound current in terms of "magnetic charges". The <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> field lines loop only around "free current=
" and, unlike the magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> field, b=
egins and ends near magnetic poles as well.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetism">Magnetism</h3></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetism" title=3D"=
Magnetism">Magnetism</a></div>
<p>Most materials respond to an applied <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></s=
pan>-field by producing their own magnetization <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=
M</b></span> and therefore their own <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span=
>-fields. Typically, the response is weak and exists only when the magnetic=
 field is applied. The term <i>magnetism</i> describes how materials respon=
d on the microscopic level to an applied magnetic field and is used to cate=
gorize the magnetic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_(matter)=
" title=3D"Phase (matter)">phase</a> of a material. Materials are divided i=
nto groups based upon their magnetic behavior:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamagnetism" title=3D"Dia=
magnetism">Diamagnetic materials</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tilley_39-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite=
_note-Tilley-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> produce a magnetization that opposes the magne=
tic field.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paramagnetism" title=3D"Parama=
gnetism">Paramagnetic materials</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tilley_39-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite=
_note-Tilley-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> produce a magnetization in the same direction =
as the applied magnetic field.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferromagnetism" title=3D"Ferro=
magnetism">Ferromagnetic materials</a> and the closely related <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferrimagnetism" title=3D"Ferrimagnetism">ferri=
magnetic materials</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antifer=
romagnetism" title=3D"Antiferromagnetism">antiferromagnetic materials</a><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Chikazumi_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Chikazumi-40"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Aharoni_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Aharoni-41"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> can have a =
magnetization independent of an applied B-field with a complex relationship=
 between the two fields.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superconductor" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Superconductor">Superconductors</a> (and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferromagnetic_superconductor" title=3D"Ferromagneti=
c superconductor">ferromagnetic superconductors</a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ben=
nemann_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
agnetic_field#cite_note-Bennemann-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lewis_=
43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic=
_field#cite_note-Lewis-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> are materials that are characterized=
 by perfect conductivity below a critical temperature and magnetic field. T=
hey also are highly magnetic and can be perfect diamagnets below a lower cr=
itical magnetic field. Superconductors often have a broad range of temperat=
ures and magnetic fields (the so-named <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Type_II_superconductor#Mixed_state" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Typ=
e II superconductor">mixed state</a>) under which they exhibit a complex hy=
steretic dependence of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> on <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>.</li></ul>
<p>In the case of paramagnetism and diamagnetism, the magnetization <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>M</b></span> is often proportional to the applied magne=
tic field such that:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \mathbf {B} =3D\mu \mathbf {H} ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">H</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbf {B} =
=3D\mu \mathbf {H} ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a575e79a4a2ae086cb8e2db0b14d3ddbd466df2d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:9.14ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbf {B} =3D\mu \mathbf {H} ,}"></span>
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BC</i></span> is a material dependent =
parameter called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permeability_=
(electromagnetism)" title=3D"Permeability (electromagnetism)">permeability<=
/a>. In some cases the permeability may be a second rank <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" title=3D"Tensor">tensor</a> so that <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> may not point in the same direction as <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>. These relations between <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> are e=
xamples of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitutive_equation" =
title=3D"Constitutive equation">constitutive equations</a>. However, superc=
onductors and ferromagnets have a more complex <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B=
</b></span>-to-<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> relation; see <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hysteresis#Magnetic_hysteresis" title=3D=
"Hysteresis">magnetic hysteresis</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Stored_energy">Stored energ=
y</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_energy" tit=
le=3D"Magnetic energy">Magnetic energy</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_hysteresis" tit=
le=3D"Magnetic hysteresis">Magnetic hysteresis</a></div>
<p>Energy is needed to generate a magnetic field both to work against the e=
lectric field that a changing magnetic field creates and to change the magn=
etization of any material within the magnetic field. For non-dispersive mat=
erials, this same energy is released when the magnetic field is destroyed s=
o that the energy can be modeled as being stored in the magnetic field.
</p><p>For linear, non-dispersive, materials (such that <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><b>B</b> =3D <i>=CE=BC</i><b>H</b></span> where <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><i>=CE=BC</i></span> is frequency-independent), the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_density" title=3D"Energy density">energy density=
</a> is:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle u=3D{\frac {\mathbf {B} \cdot \mathbf {H} }{2}}=3D{\fra=
c {\mathbf {B} \cdot \mathbf {B} }{2\mu }}=3D{\frac {\mu \mathbf {H} \cdot =
\mathbf {H} }{2}}.}">
