}{2\mu }}=3D{\frac {\mu \mathbf {H} \cdot \mathbf {H} }{2}}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/56d2a975eb0ed09b79a50affd4cfe3deb0f238fd" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.338ex; width:32.197ex; height:5.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle u=
=3D{\frac {\mathbf {B} \cdot \mathbf {H} }{2}}=3D{\frac {\mathbf {B} \cdot =
\mathbf {B} }{2\mu }}=3D{\frac {\mu \mathbf {H} \cdot \mathbf {H} }{2}}.}">=
</span>
</p><p>If there are no magnetic materials around then <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>=CE=BC</i></span> can be replaced by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=
=BC</i><sub>0</sub></span>. The above equation cannot be used for nonlinear=
 materials, though; a more general expression given below must be used.
</p><p>In general, the incremental amount of work per unit volume <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B4W</i></span> needed to cause a small change of magn=
etic field <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B4</i><b>B</b></span> is:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \delta W=3D\mathbf {H} \cdot \delta \mathbf {B} .}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CE=B4<!-- =CE=B4 --></mi>
        <mi>W</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">H</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=B4<!-- =CE=B4 --></mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \delta W=3D\m=
athbf {H} \cdot \delta \mathbf {B} .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/38cbbaed7511fa5fcbe6fd25a9c11a643ca16027" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.338ex; width:13.949ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
delta W=3D\mathbf {H} \cdot \delta \mathbf {B} .}"></span>
</p><p>Once the relationship between <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span=
> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is known this equation is use=
d to determine the work needed to reach a given magnetic state. For <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hysteresis" title=3D"Hysteresis">hysteret=
ic materials</a> such as ferromagnets and superconductors, the work needed =
also depends on how the magnetic field is created. For linear non-dispersiv=
e materials, though, the general equation leads directly to the simpler ene=
rgy density equation given above.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Appearance_in_Maxwell's_equ=
ations"><span id=3D"Appearance_in_Maxwell.27s_equations"></span>Appearance =
in Maxwell's equations</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell%27s_equation=
s" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's equations</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetism" title=
=3D"Electromagnetism">Electromagnetism</a></div>
<p>Like all vector fields, a magnetic field has two important mathematical =
properties that relates it to its <i>sources</i>. (For <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><b>B</b></span> the <i>sources</i> are currents and changing electric f=
ields.) These two properties, along with the two corresponding properties o=
f the electric field, make up <i>Maxwell's Equations</i>. Maxwell's Equatio=
ns together with the Lorentz force law form a complete description of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_electromagnetism" title=3D"Cl=
assical electromagnetism">classical electrodynamics</a> including both elec=
tricity and magnetism.
</p><p>The first property is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D=
ivergence" title=3D"Divergence">divergence</a> of a vector field <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=E2=88=87</b> =C2=
=B7 <b>A</b></span>, which represents how <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><=
/span> "flows" outward from a given point. As discussed above, a <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-field line never starts or ends at a point bu=
t instead forms a complete loop. This is mathematically equivalent to sayin=
g that the divergence of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is zero. (=
Such vector fields are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sole=
noidal_vector_field" title=3D"Solenoidal vector field">solenoidal vector fi=
elds</a>.) This property is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Gauss%27s_law_for_magnetism" title=3D"Gauss's law for magnetism">Gauss's l=
aw for magnetism</a> and is equivalent to the statement that there are no i=
solated magnetic poles or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic=
_monopole" title=3D"Magnetic monopole">magnetic monopoles</a>.
</p><p>The second mathematical property is called the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curl_(mathematics)" title=3D"Curl (mathematics)">curl</=
a>, such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=E2=88=87</b> =C3=97 <b>A</b></spa=
n> represents how <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> curls or "circula=
tes" around a given point. The result of the curl is called a "circulation =
source". The equations for the curl of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></sp=
an> and of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span> are called the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amp%C3%A8re%E2%80%93Maxwell_equation" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Amp=C3=A8re=E2=80=93Maxwell equation">Amp=C3=A8=
re=E2=80=93Maxwell equation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction" title=3D"Faraday's law of induction">Farada=
y's law</a> respectively.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Gauss'_law_for_magnetism"><=
span id=3D"Gauss.27_law_for_magnetism"></span>Gauss' law for magnetism</h3>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss%27s_law_for_ma=
gnetism" title=3D"Gauss's law for magnetism">Gauss's law for magnetism</a><=
/div>
<p>One important property of the <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-fi=
eld produced this way is that magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></sp=
an>-field lines neither start nor end (mathematically, <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><b>B</b></span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solenoida=
l_vector_field" title=3D"Solenoidal vector field">solenoidal vector field</=
a>); a field line may only extend to infinity, or wrap around to form a clo=
sed curve, or follow a never-ending (possibly chaotic) path.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-lieb_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Magnetic_field#cite_note-lieb-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Magnetic field lines exit a=
 magnet near its north pole and enter near its south pole, but inside the m=
agnet <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-field lines continue through =
the magnet from the south pole back to the north.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ex08_4=
5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_=
field#cite_note-ex08-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 11<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If a <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B=
</b></span>-field line enters a magnet somewhere it has to leave somewhere =
else; it is not allowed to have an end point.
</p><p>More formally, since all the magnetic field lines that enter any giv=
en region must also leave that region, subtracting the "number"<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-ex09_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-ex09-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>note 12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of field lines that=
 enter the region from the number that exit gives identically zero. Mathema=
tically this is equivalent to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaus=
s%27s_law_for_magnetism" title=3D"Gauss's law for magnetism">Gauss's law fo=
r magnetism</a>:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \oint _{S}\mathbf {B} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} =3D0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mo>=E2=88=AE<!-- =E2=88=AE --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>S</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=8B=85<!-- =E2=8B=85 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \oint _{S}\ma=
thbf {B} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} =3D0}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/79e91c0569752b6bf7ad9b43ad36a846c1940a72" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.338ex; width:14.125ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
oint _{S}\mathbf {B} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} =3D0}"></span>
where the integral is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_in=
tegral" title=3D"Surface integral">surface integral</a> over the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed_surface" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Closed surface">closed surface</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>S</i></sp=
an> (a closed surface is one that completely surrounds a region with no hol=
es to let any field lines escape). Since <span class=3D"texhtml">d<b>A</b><=
/span> points outward, the dot product in the integral is positive for <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-field pointing out and negative for <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>-field pointing in.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Faraday's_Law"><span id=3D"=
Faraday.27s_Law"></span>Faraday's Law</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_law_of_i=
nduction" title=3D"Faraday's law of induction">Faraday's law of induction</=
a></div>
<p>A changing magnetic field, such as a magnet moving through a conducting =
coil, generates an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_field"=
 title=3D"Electric field">electric field</a> (and therefore tends to drive =
a current in such a coil). This is known as <i>Faraday's law</i> and forms =
the basis of many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_gener=
ator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electrical generator">electrical gener=
ators</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_motor" titl=
e=3D"Electric motor">electric motors</a>. Mathematically, Faraday's law is:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\mathcal {E}}=3D-{\frac {\mathrm {d} \Phi }{\mathrm {d} t}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
