athcal {E}}}"></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elect=
romotive_force" title=3D"Electromotive force">electromotive force</a> (or <=
i>EMF</i>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voltage" title=3D"V=
oltage">voltage</a> generated around a closed loop) and <span class=3D"texh=
tml">=CE=A6</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic=
_flux" title=3D"Magnetic flux">magnetic flux</a>=E2=80=94the product of the=
 area times the magnetic field <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tan=
gential_and_normal_components" title=3D"Tangential and normal components">n=
ormal</a> to that area. (This definition of magnetic flux is why <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> is often referred to as <i>magnetic flux dens=
ity</i>.)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 210">:=E2=80=8A210=E2=80=8A</span></su=
p> The negative sign represents the fact that any current generated by a ch=
anging magnetic field in a coil produces a magnetic field that <i>opposes</=
i> the <i>change</i> in the magnetic field that induced it. This phenomenon=
 is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lenz%27s_law" title=
=3D"Lenz's law">Lenz's law</a>. This integral formulation of Faraday's law =
can be converted<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ex14_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-ex14-48"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> into a differential form, which applies under slightly different =
conditions.
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \nabla \times \mathbf {E} =3D-{\frac {\partial \mathbf =
{B} }{\partial t}}}">
