          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=82<!-- =E2=88=82 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">E</mi>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=82<!-- =E2=88=82 --></mi>
              <mi>t</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nabla \times=
 \mathbf {B} =3D\mu _{0}\mathbf {J} +\mu _{0}\varepsilon _{0}{\frac {\parti=
al \mathbf {E} }{\partial t}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/36a7ef1851c4d9440f2adb07b0cd02a48e41481b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.005ex; width:24.958ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
nabla \times \mathbf {B} =3D\mu _{0}\mathbf {J} +\mu _{0}\varepsilon _{0}{\=
frac {\partial \mathbf {E} }{\partial t}}}"></span>
</p><p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>J</b></span> is the complete micros=
copic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_density" title=3D"Cu=
rrent density">current density</a>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B5<sub>0</sub></span> is the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacuum_permittivity" title=3D"Vacuum permittivity">v=
acuum permittivity</a>.
</p><p>As discussed above, materials respond to an applied electric <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span> field and an applied magnetic <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> field by producing their own internal "bound" =
charge and current distributions that contribute to <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><b>E</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> but are diffic=
ult to calculate. To circumvent this problem, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H<=
/b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>D</b></span> fields are used to r=
e-factor Maxwell's equations in terms of the <i>free current density</i> <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><b>J</b><sub>f</sub></span>:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \nabla \times \mathbf {H} =3D\mathbf {J} _{\mathrm {f} =
}+{\frac {\partial \mathbf {D} }{\partial t}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=87<!-- =E2=88=87 --></mi>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">H</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">J</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">f</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=82<!-- =E2=88=82 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">D</mi>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=88=82<!-- =E2=88=82 --></mi>
              <mi>t</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nabla \times=
 \mathbf {H} =3D\mathbf {J} _{\mathrm {f} }+{\frac {\partial \mathbf {D} }{=
\partial t}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/380d5f3b42edfb0c7dcb8d6b4b4a060b9b5e126a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.005ex; width:19.235ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
nabla \times \mathbf {H} =3D\mathbf {J} _{\mathrm {f} }+{\frac {\partial \m=
athbf {D} }{\partial t}}}"></span>
</p><p>These equations are not any more general than the original equations=
 (if the "bound" charges and currents in the material are known). They also=
 must be supplemented by the relationship between <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>B</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> as well as that =
between <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><b>D</b></span>. On the other hand, for simple relationships between these=
 quantities this form of Maxwell's equations can circumvent the need to cal=
culate the bound charges and currents.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Formulation_in_special_rela=
tivity_and_quantum_electrodynamics">Formulation in special relativity and q=
uantum electrodynamics</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relativistic_electrodynamic=
s">Relativistic electrodynamics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relativistic_electro=
magnetism" title=3D"Relativistic electromagnetism">Relativistic electromagn=
etism</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"As_different_aspects_of_the=
_same_phenomenon">As different aspects of the same phenomenon</h4></div>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity=
" title=3D"Special relativity">the special theory of relativity</a>, the pa=
rtition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_for=
ce" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electromagnetic force">electromagnetic f=
orce</a> into separate electric and magnetic components is not fundamental,=
 but varies with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frame_of_refe=
rence#Observational_frames_of_reference" title=3D"Frame of reference">obser=
vational frame of reference</a>: An electric force perceived by one observe=
r may be perceived by another (in a different frame of reference) as a magn=
etic force, or a mixture of electric and magnetic forces.
</p><p>The magnetic field existing as electric field in other frames can be=
 shown by consistency of equations obtained from <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_transformation" title=3D"Lorentz transformation">Lor=
entz transformation</a> of four force from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Coulomb%27s_law" title=3D"Coulomb's law">Coulomb's Law</a> in part=
icle's rest frame with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell%27s=
_equations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's laws</a> considering de=
finition of fields from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_fo=
rce#Lorentz_force_law_as_the_definition_of_E_and_B" title=3D"Lorentz force"=
>Lorentz force</a><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-spa=
ce:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MOS:BROKENSECTIONL=
INKS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"MOS:BROKENSECTIONLINKS"><span title=3D=
"The anchor (Lorentz force law as the definition of E and B) has been delet=
ed. (2025-06-09)">broken anchor</span></a></i>]</sup> and for non accelerat=
ing condition. The form of magnetic field hence obtained by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_transformation" title=3D"Lorentz transfor=
mation">Lorentz transformation</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Four-force" title=3D"Four-force">four-force</a> from the form of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coulomb%27s_law" title=3D"Coulomb's law"=
>Coulomb's law</a> in source's initial frame is given by:<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Rosser1968_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Rosser1968-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refer=
ence nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 29=E2=80=9342">:=E2=80=8A29=E2=80=9342=
=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbf {B} =3D{\frac {q}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}r^{3}}}{=
\frac {1-\beta ^{2}}{(1-\beta ^{2}\sin ^{2}\theta )^{3/2}}}{\frac {\mathbf =
{v} \times \mathbf {r} }{c^{2}}}=3D{\frac {\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {E} }=
{c^{2}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">B</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>q</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mn>4</mn>
              <mi>=CF=80<!-- =CF=80 --></mi>
              <msub>
                <mi>=CE=B5<!-- =CE=B5 --></mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>0</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msup>
                <mi>r</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>3</mn>
                </mrow>
