Electromagnetic_tensor" title=3D"Electromagnetic tensor">electromagnetic te=
nsor</a></i>. Changing reference frames <i>mixes</i> these components. This=
 is analogous to the way that special relativity <i>mixes</i> space and tim=
e into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spacetime" title=3D"Spaceti=
me">spacetime</a>, and mass, momentum, and energy into <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-momentum" title=3D"Four-momentum">four-momentum</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Similarly, the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_energy" title=3D"Magnetic energ=
y">energy stored in a magnetic field</a> is mixed with the energy stored in=
 an electric field in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrom=
agnetic_stress%E2%80%93energy_tensor" title=3D"Electromagnetic stress=E2=80=
=93energy tensor">electromagnetic stress=E2=80=93energy tensor</a>.
</p>
