f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_relativity" title=3D"Theory of=
 relativity">relativity</a> it is often easier to work with a potential for=
mulation of electrodynamics rather than in terms of the electric and magnet=
ic fields. In this representation, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Magnetic_vector_potential" title=3D"Magnetic vector potential">magn=
etic vector potential</a></i> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>, and =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_potential" title=3D"E=
lectric potential">electric scalar potential</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>=CF=86</i></span>, are defined using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gauge_fixing" title=3D"Gauge fixing">gauge fixing</a> such that:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
