</p><p>The vector potential, <i><span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span></i>=
 given by this form may be interpreted as a <i>generalized potential <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Momentum" title=3D"Momentum">momentum</a=
> per unit charge</i> <sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-52"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 just as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></span> is interpreted as a <=
i>generalized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potential_energy" ti=
tle=3D"Potential energy">potential energy</a> per unit charge</i>. There ar=
e multiple choices one can make for the potential fields that satisfy the a=
bove condition. However, the choice of potentials is represented by its res=
pective gauge condition.
</p><p>Maxwell's equations when expressed in terms of the potentials in <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorenz_gauge_condition" title=3D"Lore=
nz gauge condition">Lorenz gauge</a> can be cast into a form that agrees wi=
th <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Sp=
ecial relativity">special relativity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note=
-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In relativity, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> tog=
ether with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></span> forms a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-potential" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Four-potential">four-potential</a> regardless of the gauge condition, a=
nalogous to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-vector#Four-m=
omentum" title=3D"Four-vector">four-momentum</a> that combines the momentum=
 and energy of a particle. Using the four potential instead of the electrom=
agnetic tensor has the advantage of being much simpler=E2=80=94and it can b=
e easily modified to work with quantum mechanics.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Propagation_of_Electric_and=
_Magnetic_fields">Propagation of Electric and Magnetic fields</h4></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Sp=
ecial relativity">Special theory of relativity</a> imposes the condition fo=
r events related by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causality" tit=
le=3D"Causality">cause and effect</a> to be time-like separated, that is th=
at causal efficacy propagates no faster than light.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field=
#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell=
%27s_equations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's equations</a> for e=
lectromagnetism are found to be in favor of this as electric and magnetic d=
isturbances are found to travel at the speed of light in space. Electric an=
d magnetic fields from classical electrodynamics obey the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle_of_locality" title=3D"Principle of locali=
ty">principle of locality</a> in physics and are expressed in terms of reta=
rded time or the time at which the cause of a measured field originated giv=
en that the influence of field travelled at speed of light. The retarded ti=
me for a point particle is given as solution of:
