<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Quantum_electrodynamics">Qu=
antum electrodynamics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Model" title=3D=
"Standard Model">Standard Model</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Quantum_electrodynamics" title=3D"Quantum electrodynamics">quantum el=
ectrodynamics</a></div>
<p>The classical electromagnetic field incorporated into quantum mechanics =
forms what is known as the semi-classical theory of radiation. However, it =
is not able to make experimentally observed predictions such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spontaneous_emission" title=3D"Spontaneous em=
ission">spontaneous emission process</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Lamb_shift" title=3D"Lamb shift">Lamb shift</a> implying the need=
 for quantization of fields. In modern physics, the electromagnetic field i=
s understood to be not a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classi=
cal_physics" title=3D"Classical physics">classical</a></i> <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(physics)" title=3D"Field (physics)">field</=
a>, but rather a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_field" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantum field">quantum field</a>; it is repres=
ented not as a vector of three <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rea=
l_number" title=3D"Real number">numbers</a> at each point, but as a vector =
of three <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operator_(physics)" title=
=3D"Operator (physics)">quantum operators</a> at each point. The most accur=
ate modern description of the electromagnetic interaction (and much else) i=
s <i>quantum electrodynamics</i> (QED),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-5=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> which is incorporated into a more complete theory known as t=
he <i>Standard Model of particle physics</i>.
</p><p>In QED, the magnitude of the electromagnetic interactions between ch=
arged particles (and their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antipar=
ticle" title=3D"Antiparticle">antiparticles</a>) is computed using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perturbation_theory_(quantum_mechanics)" =
title=3D"Perturbation theory (quantum mechanics)">perturbation theory</a>. =
These rather complex formulas produce a remarkable pictorial representation=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feynman_diagram" title=3D"Feyn=
man diagram">Feynman diagrams</a> in which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Virtual_photon" title=3D"Virtual photon">virtual photons</a> are e=
xchanged.
</p><p>Predictions of QED agree with experiments to an extremely high degre=
e of accuracy: currently about 10<sup>=E2=88=9212</sup> (and limited by exp=
erimental errors); for details see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Precision_tests_of_QED" title=3D"Precision tests of QED">precision tests o=
f QED</a>. This makes QED one of the most accurate physical theories constr=
ucted thus far.
</p><p>All equations in this article are in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Classical_electromagnetism" title=3D"Classical electromagneti=
sm">classical approximation</a>, which is less accurate than the quantum de=
scription mentioned here. However, under most everyday circumstances, the d=
ifference between the two theories is negligible.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Uses_and_examples">Uses and=
 examples</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Earth's_magnetic_field"><sp=
an id=3D"Earth.27s_magnetic_field"></span>Earth's magnetic field</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth%27s_magnetic_f=
ield" title=3D"Earth's magnetic field">Earth's magnetic field</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VFPt_Earths_Magnetic_Field_Confusion.svg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/f/ff/VFPt_Earths_Magnetic_Field_Confusion.svg/250px-VFPt_E=
arths_Magnetic_Field_Confusion.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" he=
ight=3D"234" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"320" data-file-he=
ight=3D"300"></a><figcaption>A sketch of Earth's magnetic field representin=
g the source of the field as a magnet. The south pole of the magnetic field=
 is near the geographic north pole of the Earth.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The Earth's magnetic field is produced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Convection" title=3D"Convection">convection</a> of a liquid iron=
 alloy in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outer_core" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Outer core">outer core</a>. In a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamo_theory" title=3D"Dynamo theory">dynamo process=
</a>, the movements drive a feedback process in which electric currents cre=
ate electric and magnetic fields that in turn act on the currents.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Weiss_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Weiss-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The field at the surface of the Earth is approximately the same as i=
f a giant bar magnet were positioned at the center of the Earth and tilted =
at an angle of about 11=C2=B0 off the rotational axis of the Earth (see the=
 figure).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The north pole =
of a magnetic compass needle points roughly north, toward the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Magnetic_Pole" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"North Magnetic Pole">North Magnetic Pole</a>. However, because a magne=
tic pole is attracted to its opposite, the North Magnetic Pole is actually =
the south pole of the geomagnetic field. This confusion in terminology aris=
es because the pole of a magnet is defined by the geographical direction it=
 points.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Earth's magnetic field is not constant=E2=80=94the strength of the f=
ield and the location of its poles vary.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-=
59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Moreover, the poles periodically reverse their orientation =
in a process called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomagnetic_re=
versal" title=3D"Geomagnetic reversal">geomagnetic reversal</a>. The <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brunhes%E2%80%93Matuyama_reversal" title=
=3D"Brunhes=E2=80=93Matuyama reversal">most recent reversal</a> occurred 78=
0,000 years ago.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rotating_magnetic_fields">R=
otating magnetic fields</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_magnetic_f=
ield" title=3D"Rotating magnetic field">Rotating magnetic field</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternator" title=3D"Alternator">Alte=
rnator</a></div>
<p>The <i>rotating magnetic field</i> is a common design principle in the o=
peration of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_motor#AC_moto=
rs" title=3D"Electric motor">alternating-current motors</a>. A permanent ma=
gnet in such a field rotates so as to maintain its alignment with the exter=
nal field.
</p><p>Magnetic torque is used to drive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Electric_motor" title=3D"Electric motor">electric motors</a>. In one =
simple motor design, a magnet is fixed to a freely rotating shaft and is su=
bjected to a magnetic field from an array of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Electromagnet" title=3D"Electromagnet">electromagnets</a>. By co=
ntinuously switching the electric current through each of the electromagnet=
s, thereby flipping the polarity of their magnetic fields, like poles are k=
ept next to the rotor; the resultant torque is transferred to the shaft.
</p><p>A rotating magnetic field can be constructed using two coils at righ=
t angles with a phase difference of 90 degrees between their AC currents. I=
n practice, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-phase_electric_p=
ower" title=3D"Three-phase electric power">three-phase</a> systems are used=
 where the three currents are equal in magnitude and have a phase differenc=
e of 120 degrees. Three similar coils at mutual geometrical angles of 120 d=
egrees create the rotating magnetic field. The ability of the three-phase s=
ystem to create a rotating field, utilized in electric motors, is one of th=
e main reasons why three-phase systems dominate the world's <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Electrical power">electrical power</a> supply systems.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synchronous_motor" title=3D=
"Synchronous motor">Synchronous motors</a> use DC-voltage-fed rotor winding=
s, which lets the excitation of the machine be controlled=E2=80=94and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Induction_motor" title=3D"Induction mot=
or">induction motors</a> use short-circuited <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rotor_(electric)" title=3D"Rotor (electric)">rotors</a> (instead=
 of a magnet) following the rotating magnetic field of a multicoiled <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stator" title=3D"Stator">stator</a>. The=
 short-circuited turns of the rotor develop <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Eddy_current" title=3D"Eddy current">eddy currents</a> induced by=
 the rotating field of the stator, and these currents in turn produce a tor=
que on the rotor through the Lorentz force.
</p><p>The Italian physicist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galil=
eo_Ferraris" title=3D"Galileo Ferraris">Galileo Ferraris</a> and the Serbia=
n-American <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_engineer" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electrical engineer">electrical engineer</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikola_Tesla" title=3D"Nikola Tesla=
">Nikola Tesla</a> independently researched the use of rotating magnetic fi=
elds in electric motors. In 1888, Ferraris published his research in a pape=
r to the <i>Royal Academy of Sciences</i> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Turin" title=3D"Turin">Turin</a> and Tesla gained <span><a rel=
=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://patents.google.com/pa=
tent/US381968">U.S. patent 381,968</a></span> for his work.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hall_effect">Hall effect</h=
3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hall_effect" title=
=3D"Hall effect">Hall effect</a></div>
<p>The charge carriers of a current-carrying conductor placed in a transver=
se magnetic field experience a sideways Lorentz force; this results in a ch=
arge separation in a direction perpendicular to the current and to the magn=
etic field. The resultant voltage in that direction is proportional to the =
applied magnetic field. This is known as the <i>Hall effect</i>.
</p><p>The <i>Hall effect</i> is often used to measure the magnitude of a m=
agnetic field. It is used as well to find the sign of the dominant charge c=
arriers in materials such as semiconductors (negative electrons or positive=
 holes).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Magnetic_circuits">Magnetic=
 circuits</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_circuit" ti=
tle=3D"Magnetic circuit">Magnetic circuit</a></div>
<p>An important use of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span> is in <i>mag=
netic circuits</i> where <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b> =3D <i>=CE=BC</i>=
<b>H</b></span> inside a linear material. Here, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
=CE=BC</i></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_=
permeability" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Magnetic permeability">magneti=
c permeability</a> of the material. This result is similar in form to <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohm%27s_law" title=3D"Ohm's law">Ohm's =
law</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>J</b> =3D <i>=CF=83</i><b>E</b></span>, =
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>J</b></span> is the current density, <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=83</i></span> is the conductance and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>E</b></span> is the electric field. Extending this analogy,=
 the counterpart to the macroscopic Ohm's law (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>I=
</i> =3D <i>V</i>=E2=81=84<i>R</i></span>) is:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
