uctance</a> of the circuit. Here the reluctance <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
R</i><sub>m</sub></span> is a quantity similar in nature to <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_resistance" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Electrical resistance">resistance</a> for the flux. Using this analogy=
 it is straightforward to calculate the magnetic flux of complicated magnet=
ic field geometries, by using all the available techniques of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Circuit theory">circuit theory</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Largest_magnitude_magnetic_=
fields">Largest magnitude magnetic fields</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1305433154"><table class=3D"box-Update plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-cont=
ent ambox-Update" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image"=
><div class=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><span><img alt=3D""=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_cur=
rent_red.svg/60px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"42=
" height=3D"34" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"360" data-file=
-height=3D"290"></span></span></div></td><td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=
=3D"mbox-text-span">This section needs to be <b>updated</b>.<span class=3D"=
hide-when-compact"> Please help update this article to reflect recent event=
s or newly available information. <br><small>Last update: October 2018</sma=
ll></span>  <span class=3D"date-container"><i>(<span class=3D"date">July 20=
21</span>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>As of October 2018<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag up=
date" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMagnetic_field&amp;action=3Dedit">[updat=
e]</a></sup>, the largest magnitude magnetic field produced over a macrosco=
pic volume outside a lab setting is 2.8&nbsp;kT (<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/VNIIEF" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"VNIIEF">VNIIEF</a> in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarov" title=3D"Sarov">Sarov</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia" title=3D"Russia">Russia</=
a>, 1998).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-smithsonianMagnetRecord_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-smithsonianMagnetRecord-62"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> As of October 2018, the largest magnitude magnetic field produce=
d in a laboratory over a macroscopic volume was 1.2&nbsp;kT by researchers =
at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Tokyo" title=
=3D"University of Tokyo">University of Tokyo</a> in 2018.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-smithsonianMagnetRecord_62-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-smithsonianMagnetRecord-62"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
The largest magnitude magnetic fields produced in a laboratory occur in par=
ticle accelerators, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relati=
vistic_Heavy_Ion_Collider" title=3D"Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider">RHIC</=
a>, inside the collisions of heavy ions, where microscopic fields reach 10<=
sup>14</sup>&nbsp;T.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-63"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Magnetar" title=3D"Magnetar">Magnetars</a> have the strongest k=
nown magnetic fields of any naturally occurring object, ranging from 0.1 to=
 100&nbsp;GT (10<sup>8</sup> to 10<sup>11</sup>&nbsp;T).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-65" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_=
field#cite_note-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
