<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_electroma=
gnetic_theory" title=3D"History of electromagnetic theory">History of elect=
romagnetic theory</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_electromagne=
tism_and_classical_optics" title=3D"Timeline of electromagnetism and classi=
cal optics">Timeline of electromagnetism and classical optics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Descartes_magnetic_field.jpg" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/5/5d/Descartes_magnetic_field.jpg/330px-Descartes_magnetic_field.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"255" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"1372" data-file-height=3D"1165"></a><figcaption>One of th=
e first drawings of a magnetic field, by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descart=
es</a>, 1644, showing the Earth attracting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Lodestone" title=3D"Lodestone">lodestones</a>. It illustrated his =
theory that magnetism was caused by the circulation of tiny helical particl=
es, "threaded parts", through threaded pores in magnets.</figcaption></figu=
re>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Early_developments">Early d=
evelopments</h3></div>
<p>While magnets and some properties of magnetism were known to ancient soc=
ieties, the research of magnetic fields began in 1269 when French scholar <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petrus_Peregrinus_de_Maricourt" tit=
le=3D"Petrus Peregrinus de Maricourt">Petrus Peregrinus de Maricourt</a> ma=
pped out the magnetic field on the surface of a spherical magnet using iron=
 needles. Noting the resulting field lines crossed at two points he named t=
hose points "poles" in analogy to Earth's poles. He also articulated the pr=
inciple that magnets always have both a north and south pole, no matter how=
 finely one slices them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-66"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>note 14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Almost three centuries later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/William_Gilbert_(astronomer)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"William Gil=
bert (astronomer)">William Gilbert</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Colchester" title=3D"Colchester">Colchester</a> replicated Petrus P=
eregrinus' work and was the first to state explicitly that Earth is a magne=
t.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 34">=
:=E2=80=8A34=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Published in 1600, Gilbert's work, <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Magnete" title=3D"De Magnete">De =
Magnete</a></i>, helped to establish magnetism as a science.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mathematical_development">M=
athematical development</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted,_Der_Geist_in_der_=
Natur,_1854.tiff" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.=
wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted%2C_De=
r_Geist_in_der_Natur%2C_1854.tiff/lossy-page1-250px-Hans_Christian_%C3%98rs=
ted%2C_Der_Geist_in_der_Natur%2C_1854.tiff.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"383" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1936" dat=
a-file-height=3D"2968"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted" title=3D"Hans Christian =C3=98rsted">Hans =
Christian =C3=98rsted</a>, <i>Der Geist in der Natur</i>, 1854</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>In 1750, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Michell" title=3D=
"John Michell">John Michell</a> stated that magnetic poles attract and repe=
l in accordance with an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_sq=
uare_law" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inverse square law">inverse square=
 law</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 56">:=E2=
=80=8A56=E2=80=8A</span></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cha=
rles-Augustin_de_Coulomb" title=3D"Charles-Augustin de Coulomb">Charles-Aug=
ustin de Coulomb</a> experimentally verified this in 1785 and stated explic=
itly that north and south poles cannot be separated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whi=
ttaker1910_68-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refe=
rence nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 59">:=E2=80=8A59=E2=80=8A</span></sup> B=
uilding on this force between poles, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sim%C3%A9on_Denis_Poisson" title=3D"Sim=C3=A9on Denis Poisson">Sim=C3=A9=
on Denis Poisson</a> (1781=E2=80=931840) created the first successful model=
 of the magnetic field, which he presented in 1824.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whit=
taker1910_68-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refer=
ence nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 64">:=E2=80=8A64=E2=80=8A</span></sup> In=
 this model, a magnetic <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>-field is pr=
oduced by <i>magnetic poles</i> and magnetism is due to small pairs of nort=
h=E2=80=93south magnetic poles.
</p><p>Three discoveries in 1820 challenged this foundation of magnetism. <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted" title=
=3D"Hans Christian =C3=98rsted">Hans Christian =C3=98rsted</a> demonstrated=
 that a current-carrying wire is surrounded by a circular magnetic field.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>n=
ote 15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-70=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fie=
ld#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Then <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re" title=3D"Andr=C3=A9-Marie Amp=C3=A8re">Andr=
=C3=A9-Marie Amp=C3=A8re</a> showed that parallel wires with currents attra=
ct one another if the currents are in the same direction and repel if they =
are in opposite directions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-5" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_no=
te-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=
=3D"Page: 87">:=E2=80=8A87=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#ci=
te_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Finally, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J=
ean-Baptiste_Biot" title=3D"Jean-Baptiste Biot">Jean-Baptiste Biot</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Savart" title=3D"F=C3=
=A9lix Savart">F=C3=A9lix Savart</a> announced empirical results about the =
forces that a current-carrying long, straight wire exerted on a small magne=
t, determining the forces were inversely proportional to the perpendicular =
distance from the wire to the magnet.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tricker23_72-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#c=
ite_note-Tricker23-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-6"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fiel=
d#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><s=
pan title=3D"Page: 86">:=E2=80=8A86=E2=80=8A</span></sup> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Laplace">La=
place</a> later deduced a law of force based on the differential action of =
a differential section of the wire,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tricker23_72-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cit=
e_note-Tricker23-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-73"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> which became known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Biot%E2%80%93Savart_law" title=3D"Biot=E2=80=93Savart law">Biot=E2=80=93Sav=
art law</a>, as Laplace did not publish his findings.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_fie=
ld#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Extending these experiments, Amp=C3=A8re published his own successfu=
l model of magnetism in 1825. In it, he showed the equivalence of electrica=
l currents to magnets<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-7" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whi=
ttaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pa=
ge: 88">:=E2=80=8A88=E2=80=8A</span></sup> and proposed that magnetism is d=
ue to perpetually flowing loops of current instead of the dipoles of magnet=
ic charge in Poisson's model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-75"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Further, Amp=C3=A8re derived both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Amp%C3%A8re%27s_force_law" title=3D"Amp=C3=A8re's force law">Amp=
=C3=A8re's force law</a> describing the force between two currents and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amp%C3%A8re%27s_law" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Amp=C3=A8re's law">Amp=C3=A8re's law</a>, which, like the Bio=
t=E2=80=93Savart law, correctly described the magnetic field generated by a=
 steady current. Also in this work, Amp=C3=A8re introduced the term <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrodynamics" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Electrodynamics">electrodynamics</a> to describe the relationship be=
tween electricity and magnetism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-8" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#ci=
te_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span =
title=3D"Pages: 88=E2=80=9392">:=E2=80=8A88=E2=80=9392=E2=80=8A</span></sup=
>
</p><p>In 1831, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Faraday" t=
itle=3D"Michael Faraday">Michael Faraday</a> discovered <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_induction" title=3D"Electromagnetic i=
nduction">electromagnetic induction</a> when he found that a changing magne=
tic field generates an encircling electric field, formulating what is now k=
nown as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_law_of_inducti=
on" title=3D"Faraday's law of induction">Faraday's law of induction</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 189=E2=80=93192">:=
=E2=80=8A189=E2=80=93192=E2=80=8A</span></sup> Later, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Ernst_Neumann" title=3D"Franz Ernst Neumann">Fran=
z Ernst Neumann</a> proved that, for a moving conductor in a magnetic field=
, induction is a consequence of Amp=C3=A8re's force law.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Whittaker1910_68-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D=
"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 222">:=E2=80=8A222=E2=80=8A</span><=
/sup> In the process, he introduced the magnetic vector potential, which wa=
s later shown to be equivalent to the underlying mechanism proposed by Fara=
day.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 225">:=E2=80=
=8A225=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>In 1850, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lord_Kelvin" title=
=3D"Lord Kelvin">Lord Kelvin</a>, then known as William Thomson, distinguis=
hed between two magnetic fields now denoted <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b=
></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span>. The former applied to=
 Poisson's model and the latter to Amp=C3=A8re's model and induction.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 224">:=E2=80=8A224=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup> Further, he derived how <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b=
></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> relate to each other a=
nd coined the term <i>permeability</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Whittaker1910_68=
-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_=
field#cite_note-Whittaker1910-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap=
"><span title=3D"Page: 245">:=E2=80=8A245=E2=80=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
gnetic_field#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Between 1861 and 1865, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jame=
s_Clerk_Maxwell" title=3D"James Clerk Maxwell">James Clerk Maxwell</a> deve=
loped and published <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell%27s_eq=
uations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's equations</a>, which expla=
ined and united all of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_t=
heory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Classical theory">classical</a> elect=
ricity and magnetism. The first set of these equations was published in a p=
aper entitled <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCC=
ommons:File:On_Physical_Lines_of_Force.pdf&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D=
1" class=3D"new" title=3D"CCommons:File:On Physical Lines of Force.pdf (pag=
e does not exist)">On Physical Lines of Force</a></i> in 1861. These equati=
ons were valid but incomplete. Maxwell completed his set of equations in hi=
s later 1865 paper <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Dynamical_=
Theory_of_the_Electromagnetic_Field" title=3D"A Dynamical Theory of the Ele=
ctromagnetic Field">A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field</a></i>=
 and demonstrated the fact that light is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_wave" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electromagne=
tic wave">electromagnetic wave</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Heinrich_Hertz" title=3D"Heinrich Hertz">Heinrich Hertz</a> published pap=
ers in 1887 and 1888 experimentally confirming this fact.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-h202_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
agnetic_field#cite_note-h202-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite=
_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modern_developments">Modern=
 developments</h3></div>
<p>In 1887, Tesla developed an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ind=
uction_motor" title=3D"Induction motor">induction motor</a> that ran on <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternating_current" title=3D"Alterna=
ting current">alternating current</a>. The motor used <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyphase_system" title=3D"Polyphase system">polyphase<=
/a> current, which generated a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rot=
ating_magnetic_field" title=3D"Rotating magnetic field">rotating magnetic f=
ield</a> to turn the motor (a principle that Tesla claimed to have conceive=
d in 1882).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magn=
etic_field#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-81">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> Tesla received a patent for his electric motor in May 1888.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#cite=
_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> In 1885, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gal=
ileo_Ferraris" title=3D"Galileo Ferraris">Galileo Ferraris</a> independentl=
y researched rotating magnetic fields and subsequently published his resear=
ch in a paper to the <i>Royal Academy of Sciences</i> in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turin" title=3D"Turin">Turin</a>, just two months be=
fore Tesla was awarded his patent, in March 1888.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-84" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_field#c=
ite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The twentieth century showed that classical electrodynamics is alrea=
dy consistent with special relativity, and extended classical electrodynami=
cs to work with quantum mechanics. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Albert_Einstein" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Albert Einstein</a>, in his pap=
er of 1905 that established relativity, showed that both the electric and m=
agnetic fields are part of the same phenomena viewed from different referen=
ce frames. Finally, the emergent field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a=
> was merged with electrodynamics to form <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Quantum_electrodynamics" title=3D"Quantum electrodynamics">quantum =
electrodynamics</a>, which first formalized the notion that electromagnetic=
 field energy is quantized in the form of photons.
</p>
